headline: Pelosi's leadership criticized after Dems' losing streak
subHeadline: Democrats' dismal record has some questioning whether the House minority leader should keep her job

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello, everyone, I am Dana Perino along with Kimberly Guilfoyle, Juan Williams, Jesse Watters and Greg Gutfeld. It is 9 o'clock in New York City and this is "The Five." The Democrats are on a losing streak despite the near incessant accusations of presidential obstruction of justice and unconstitutional actions. The Democrats are now 0 for 4 in Congressional special elections for seats vacated by Trump appointees. The Democrats issues were on full display on Tuesday after the GOP netted two wins in special elections in Georgia and South Carolina. This is despite unprecedented spending by liberals. President Trump brought up the Republican victories last night at his rally in Iowa.

utterances.speaker: PRESIDENT DONALD TRUMP
utterances.sentences: Their plan isn't working because they thought they were going to win last night in Atlanta. They thought they were going to win. And they have been unbelievably nasty. Really nasty.  All we do is win, win, win. We won last night. They can't believe it. They say, what is going on? What is going on? We won last night. And even the worst of them said, "That was a big win for Trump."

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: The results have even some Democrats questioning whether House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi should keep her job.

utterances.speaker: DON LEMON, CNN ANCHOR
utterances.sentences: Do think Nancy Pelosi is more toxic than Donald Trump?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: You know what? The honest answer is, in some areas of the country, yes, she is.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Nancy Pelosi is a great speaker. She is a great leader. But her time has come and gone. Yes, she's a great fundraiser but if the money that we are raising through her leadership is not helping us win elections, then we have to have this difficult conversation now.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Liberal co-maker Michael Moore echoed that sentiment, tweeting out that the Democrats, quote, "Have no message, no plan, no leaders." As for Ms. Pelosi herself, she is brushing off the criticism and is as confident as ever.

utterances.speaker: REP. NANCY PELOSI (D-CA), MINORITY LEADER
utterances.sentences: Do you want me to sing my praises? Is that what you're saying? I am a master legislator. I am a strategic politically astute leader. My leadership is recognized by many around the country and that is why I am able to attract the support that I do. Which is essential to our election, sad to say.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And today, President Trump tweeted that he does not want Pelosi out. He said, "I certainly hope the Democrats do not force Nancy P out. That would be very bad for the Republican Party. And please, let crying Chuck stay. "So, take a look at this headlines, Jesse. This is from around the beltway. This is all about Nancy Pelosi being in the hot seat. But I just wonder if they're actually going to oust her. You know, they tried in the beginning of the Congress and she is like held strong. She is a big national fundraiser for them. And she actually enforces party discipline, better than anybody so far. Do you think she stays or goes?

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: I think she goes. But then the coup attempt, if it's not successful, then the knives come out. Because everybody knows who voted for who. That is the danger there. You have to be sure that she's going to fall in order to take the action. But I just don't think Pelosi fundamentally understands America or Americans. And I don't think the Democratic Party is self-aware enough to realize that she cannot be the face of the party because she doesn't play outside of the state of California. She had a nice run.  You know, she took charge in 2006 after the Iraq war went South and after some Republican scandals. And then she pushed through ObamaCare, the stimulus disasters, misread the will of the American people and then she got bounced out in 2010 when the Tea Party wave took over. But according to the latest polling, nearly half of the country believes the Democratic Party has become too extreme. That's up eight points over the last year. And the whole Democratic message under Pelosi is built on fantasy. Free college. Free health care. Russia. So, I don't know how many moral victories the Democrats are going to be able to stomach before they realized it's time to actually start winning. You know, President Trump like to say, you know, we are going to win so much, you are going to be sick of winning. Are the Democrats sick of losing yet? We are not really sure. And I think one of the side effects of Trump derangement syndrome is short-term memory loss.  Because the Democrats have forgot about the issue. The Democrats actually are competitive when they talk about Medicare, college tuition, wages, things of that nature but when they go off on identity politics and Russia, Russia, Russia, they lose the resistance -- it fails. It's not a winning message. And I think actual Democrats in the heartland wish the D.C. Democrats are obsessed over them instead of obsessing over Russia.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Juan, there is a new poll from the Wall Street Journal NBC that says that on the economy that the majority of Americans think Republicans are on the right track and they're the ones that would do a better job in the economy and enforce the change that's needed. So, the Democrats are having this fight amongst themselves and Michael Moore is saying they don't have a message, they don't have a plan. Is it time for them to make some sort of change?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Well, I think that is the real discussion. I mean, obviously, you know, Republicans will delight in the demise of Nancy Pelosi. They beat her up. I mean, you and I were talking on the show a few days or a few nights ago about the idea, you know, what is this demonization of politicians and the nastiness? And you watch the ads that played down in Georgia six, and they were all about Nancy Pelosi and they had Ossoff taking off the mask revealing that he was really Pelosi and this R-left Democrats. I mean --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: It's not funny.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: This plays to Republican taste in a big way. That's why President Trump is saying, don't go anywhere near Nancy. We love her.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Maybe that's, Kimberly means that -- maybe it's not about her personally but that the Republicans have been able to successfully brand her as the one that you want to fight against. And so, it's actually been successful. And maybe, I mean, I don't think -- I am very impressed with her career.

utterances.speaker: KIMBERLY GUILFOYLE, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Absolutely.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And she's 77 years old. She's been able to do a lot for the Democrats. So, I think there's something to be said for all that she's done. I also don't think she's going anywhere.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Yes. And I know Nancy a very long time. And her whole family, you know, back in San Francisco. And she's very hard-working. She's done all of this and made a lot of personal sacrifice in terms of trying to serve the country. I give her credit for that and being a woman in a strong position. Now, that being the case, believe me, but Republicans are not going to delight in her demise. They want to prop wrap. There's by more Republicans supporting her staying in place. And Chuck Schumer staying in place, and crazy Tom Perez, you know, at the DNC, let them stay. Okay. Those three kings. Like, let them be in their place. Because it's not helping. However, I do think in this case, she's being a little bit scapegoated. The big problem, I will touch on what Jessie said is the Democratic Party. Their insane psychotic rage against the Trump presidency, like they rage against the Trump candidacy, and there is an obsession with that, that now they are a party with no platform.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Uh-hm.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: -- with no bench. And kind of know where to go. At least Nancy Pelosi knows how to raise the money. I'm just telling you. Who else is going to step up to take that place to be the one who can make all the phone calls and get the money? The problem is, they don't know how to spend the money that they got. They are doing it and all the wrong ways. They turned this into a referendum against to President Trump instead of keeping it local in grass roots. And made it this whole like, you know, nationwide thing, you know, in district six instead of just getting right there in the front and back yards of the people they were talking to.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Can we get Greg in?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Karen Handel never mentioned Trump once.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, I think that's why the Republicans were smart. And he stayed away from her as well.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But you don't hear anybody saying, oh, get rid of Trump. Trump's numbers are like, you know, 35-40 percent. Her numbers are about 30, 35 percent. They are both not popular.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right. Let's get Greg in. Because it's not just one person that's a problem.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: It doesn't matter. It doesn't matter if Nancy Pelosi stays or if she goes. It's the party.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yep.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: And Michael Moore is dead right on this. The big difference between Trump and the Democratic Party is Trump, there is promise. I'm going to help you, here is what we are going to do. The Dems, there is no promise or even more, there is no redemption. Meaning that if you actually try to agree with the Democrats, it's too late. Especially if you are white. If you are white, privileged, part of the patriarchy, you are doomed.  So, right now they have splintered the country because they replaced life experience with identity. We talked about identity politics. So, America now is fall for anything. And that means that you can't have the singular identity of being an American.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Because that represents everything that's evil. And so, you replaced that with hundreds of competing tribes. All of these different pronounce and identities. So, the Democratic Party is no longer a singular entity. It's like Sybil. Do you remember Sybil? A collection of combative corralling voices.   Yes. And they are eating themselves live. If you look on the campuses, what's happened at Evergreen, they are actually going after their own. If you take identity politics out of the equation, the Democratic Party, it's like taking meatballs out of a meatball sandwich, there is nothing there. The Democratic Party can no longer say what they're for. They can only say what they are against. And they are against so many things. They aren't just against Trump. They are against people who voted for Trump. They are against gasoline. They are against meat.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Weather.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know, they're against anything. They're against individual liberty. Right? They're against -- I never thought -- you never thought you would see the day, especially one, they are against speech. They are not even -- they are the ones that are trying to silence people on campus. It is not the right, it's the left.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: They're against everything except Sharia Law and the abuse of women and children and gays, I mean, that's what they aren't against.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Let me go -- we want to turn now to some tape that we just came across of actor Johnny Depp today at the Glastonbury Festival in the U.K.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Look at them.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: The "Pirates of the Caribbean" started joking earlier, apparently he was joking about assassinating President Trump.

utterances.speaker: JOHNNY DEPP, ACTOR
utterances.sentences: I think he needs help. When was the last time an actor assassinated a president?  I want to clarify, I am not an actor.  I lie for a living.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right. Greg, what do you make of that?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He is a mess. He is an absolute mess. The guy -- this is your prominent mouthpiece. What I'm talking about, it's like, this is a guy who is obviously in lots of trouble. So, I feel kind of sorry for him. He looks like a vintage lampshade from a thrift shop.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: It's not that good.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He is trying to be Keith Richards every time he opens his mouth that obviously he's messed up. And it's kind of sad he thinks the President is messed up when he is talking he can barely focus.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Man in the mirror.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I mean, asked the secret service they are cool with celebrities making assassination jokes or beheading people or putting on assassination plays. The guys that are paid to protect the President, Republican or Democrat, they don't like these jokes. These jokes are funny. We were talking earlier though, you know, the President likes to keep Nancy Pelosi around because she's kind of fires up the Republican base and she makes the Democrats look bad. You know, I'd say keep Johnny Depp around. Because, you know, this is the kind of guy that Hollywood brings into a place like Georgia sixth --

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And just ruins it for the candidates on the left. I mean, this can't keep happening over and over and over again.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Juan, do you think that the Democrats have a Hollywood problem? Do you think --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Good question.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- that is a real thing.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, I think some of the people on the far left, especially the Hollywood types. And here, I would agree with Greg, you know, I think sometimes the condescension is just over leaning. It just becomes like, we don't like you, we don't know you, we don't care about the reality of your lives or how you think. And I think you can't. That kind of arrogance is very unappealing. Who wants to, you know, do business with somebody who's not listening? And so, to me, but I will say this. It's wrong to think that Johnny Depp would have been in Georgia six. Ossoff ran as a middle of the road guy and didn't emphasize the Bernie Sanders type thing.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Jane Fonda and Chelsea Handler and Alyssa Milano --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, no, no. What you get is people coming in and drawing attention to Ossoff but not these far left positions that you guys delight in.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: No, no, no. It's all over the mainstream media. And you see the celebrities going off, every day going cycle. Foaming at the mouth with the mainstream media. This vitriol, the rage, plus the millions of dollars from California was enough to take everybody off and really motivate Republican base to come out and support Karen. And that's why she won.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Let me just say, you know, remember right now in polls, Democrats are up plus seven to plus 10 in terms of a generic Congressional ballot.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: For 2018. That's true.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes. For 2018. So, that means something is going on that guess what, people don't like what the Republicans are doing. We are going to talk about something specifically in the next segment.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right. President Trump is blasting the Democrats for trying to block his efforts to repeal and replace ObamaCare. Details ahead.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Senate Republicans released their planned today that once and for all, repeal and replace ObamaCare. President Trump says he willing to negotiate over the details but Democrats won't even come to the table.

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.sentences: ObamaCare is a disaster. It's dead. Totally dead and we are putting in a plan today that is going to be negotiated. We would love to have some Democrats support but they are obstructionists. We won't get one, no matter how good it is. But we will hopefully get something done and it will be something with heart. And very meaningful.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: President Obama for his part blasted the Republican plan, posting a lengthy statement on Facebook that said in part, quote, "This bill will do you harm." And no matter what changes the Republicans make it, they cannot change the fundamental meanness at the core of this legislation. So, Greg, I am not saying this is perfect bill by any stretch of the imagination but, you know, when Democrats criticized this, it kind of reminds me of the football coach that goes 0 and 16, gets fired and then starts chirping from these bleachers about the game plan of the next coach. He has no credibility.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: The brilliance of President Obama, no matter how bad ObamaCare is, it was going to be impossible to remove.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Like I said before it's like gum in your hair once it's there. But the thing that struck me was the Democrat response especially after the Scalise shooting, when we were talking about, you know, bad language and violent imagery. And you have Liz Warren saying, calling this blood money. Paying for tax cuts with American lives and you wonder why these things happen, Liz. Huh? You should maybe watch yourself saying those things. After what happened. And then what's interesting, they are having these die-ins because Republicans kill people. That's what we do. Isn't that the inflammatory language we were talking about? You are staging a die in. And by the way, how are they able to plan that die-in so immediately after reading the 142 page report which was released today? So, everybody there read the report. They already knew it and they just instantaneously show up for a die-in.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Anybody who does has a die-in also --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Now, there was a die-in this morning at Central Park when I was walking Jasper. The bill hadn't even been released.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I think that was at Central Park.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: That was a wine in.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That was a wine in. I think I'm going to be there tomorrow. Kimberly, there is a few conservative senators that have now come out and said, you know, what, I don't like this thing. And do you think that's going to be a problem?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Well, it's not great. Right? Because it's enough to create a problem for it not to get through. Obviously the President would like to see unanimous support. I mean, right? That would be a good idea.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Uh-hm.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: And then say, listen, we understand. We hear your objections. And this is how we plan to address them going forward. Well, let's put this in and face it out. At least that was the argument that they were making before. There they are. These -- on the four.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: And so, they made some comments before that this wasn't able to get through.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: That they had problems with it. And then they tried to address some of those problems. You are not going to please everybody but a margin this type, they cannot afford to lose anybody.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I think that it could be a strategy.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Which would be what?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I think it's that Senator McConnell knew that the right guy, the conservatives, whatever they're calling themselves, that they were going to be against it. And so in the next week or so, as they try to offer amendments, basically what you have to do is you have keep this bill -- enough for House Republicans to vote on it and conference.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: So, I think this is a little bit of like, okay, I'm glad that they are actually doing this so then they can try to keep it in a conservative direction so that I can pass the House.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Okay. Interesting concept. Juan, anything is better than ObamaCare?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, I don't think so. And this is obviously not better. I love the fact that they call it better health care. I'm thinking. Okay. So, are more people insured? No no, no, no. How about this? The premiums go down? No. What about the American Hospital Association? Let's get above the politics. Let's go to the people who provide health care, what did they say? This is going to drive up premiums and cause for working people who come to the hospital. But what about the elderly, Jesse? The people in nursing homes. The people who we all have sympathy for.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: They are all going to let them die according to the liberals. You want to say it, Juan.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I know you want to say it, Juan. Go ahead.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I want to say tick them up because I know if I say die or push grandma off the cliff -- if you are putting a cap on Medicaid and people are in nursing homes -- that's how the nursing home gets paid, you are pushing people. So, the fact --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Almost there.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: You forgot children dying of cancer.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: It's too much, we don't have so much time. The fact that you have a bill, the house eight percent support across the nation? Bill, that's the basis for the Senate bill and the Senate bill really doesn't improve it. Remember, the President said, the House bill was mean. This is really not --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: But Juan, but Juan, the polls -- can I just say this?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: The polls are measuring what people don't like it, what the media is saying about.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, no.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Because they're getting their information from you.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: People are not stupid. And let me just say --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Is that how you guys past ObamaCare because --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: The real opposition here, Susan Collins, Shelley Moore Capito --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Juan, we can refute all your things point by point but instead we will going to talk to Ainsley Earhardt who spoke to President Trump about health care. Roll the tape.

utterances.speaker: AINSLEY EARHARDT, FOX NEWS CORRESPONDENT
utterances.sentences: You have the House and the Senate but you have these senators that are now on board.

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.sentences: Well, there are also four good guys and four friends of mine. And I think that they will probably get there. We will have to see. You know, health care is a very difficult situation. If you look, the Clintons tried to get it and after years and years, they couldn't do it. ObamaCare was murder for them to get. And now it has failed. It's virtually out of business. ObamaCare is a disaster. And we are trying to do something in a very short period of time.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Okay. So, the President is basically this has got to go through, you know, you could see a huge momentum shift for the President, you know, off the heels of this Comey stuff and this Mueller investigation. You know, health care passes, tax reform gets teed up. The economy starts jamming up again. This could be a turning point. What do you think?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, yes, in theory. And I think actually, you could actually get there but the next two weeks, they are not going to be smooth.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And it's going to be ugly.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Absolutely. Because at least, one thing about Nancy Pelosi and Reid before Chuck Schumer, they could actually keep their people rigorously --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: They ruled with an iron fist.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: They did. They said, we are all voting together. We're voting a block. Republicans are much more for individualism. Right? They're like, everybody can have their own opinion and is just a little bit more messy but I think by the end of it, if they get it for the President to sign, it will be better legislation. It won't be what everybody wants but it will hopefully increase competition which will help decrease cost.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: After seven years. Seven years. Repeal. We're going to repeal it. No repeal. It's what Greg said.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: President Obama illegally transferred fronds from the Treasury Department in order to pay for ObamaCare. It was not even self-sustaining. That's why it's --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: It's been self-sustaining. It's been sabotaged by Republicans.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: And if you don't like it so much, maybe you can reach across the aisle and maybe get --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I agree with that point.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know what ObamaCare is? It's like, one of the -- it's a huge awful tattoo that you got in your 20s. On your back. And it's like really hard to remove. And it is going to take a long time to remove it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: They are talking about Medicaid, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes, I understand.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: They are actually saving and strengthening Medicaid, Juan.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Include tattoo removal on that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: All right. And you guys can see Ainsley's full interview with President Trump tomorrow morning on "Fox & FRIENDS." President Trump says he doesn't want a poor person to run the economy. Is that a good idea? We will going to discuss it, up next.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: There you go. A fired up President Trump addressed supporters at a rally in Iowa last night, touting his administration's accomplishments in front of a jubilant crowd of thousands. But listen to this provocative comment from Mr. Trump while lauding the business accomplishments of his top economic advisors.

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.sentences: So somebody said, why did you appoint a rich person to be in charge of the economy?

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.sentences: I said -- no, it's true. And Wilbur is a very rich person in charge of commerce. I said because that's the kind of thinking we want. I mean, you know, really, because they are representing the country. They don't want the money. They love all people, rich or poor. But in those particular positions, I just don't want a poor person. Does that make sense? Does that make sense?

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.sentences: If you insist, I will do it. But I like it better this way, right?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: OK, how many people know what he meant by that, raise your hand?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I'm seeing four hands so far. Juan Williams is confused.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I'm confused. I'm curious. What do you think he meant by that?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Wilbur Ross has been very successful. He is brilliant. He is in charge of commerce. You have Steven Mnuchin who is in charge of the treasury department. You have Gary Cohen advising on the economy as well. So these are people who have been very successful, because they've been able to figure out the economic puzzle and the way to succeed in the country. And so, when President Trump ran for office, he said I wanted to get the best and brightest out there available to help me...

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Wait a second, wait a second.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Can I interrupt?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: He didn't say that. He said the richest.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: No, no, no.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: He didn't say these are people who are experts.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.sentences: I said when he ran for office, this is what he promised.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS

utterances.utterance: -- with no bench. And kind of know where to go. At least Nancy Pelosi knows how to raise the money. I'm just telling you. utterances.utterance: Yep.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: And Michael Moore is dead right on this. The big difference between Trump and the Democratic Party is Trump, there is promise. utterances.utterance: Because that represents everything that's evil. And so, you replaced that with hundreds of competing tribes. All of these different pronounce and identities. utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know, they're against anything. They're against individual liberty. Right? utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: They're against everything except Sharia Law and the abuse of women and children and gays, I mean, that's what they aren't against.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Let me go -- we want to turn now to some tape that we just came across of actor Johnny Depp today at the Glastonbury Festival in the U.K.

utterances.utterance: He is a mess. He is an absolute mess. The guy -- this is your prominent mouthpiece. What I'm talking about, it's like, this is a guy who is obviously in lots of trouble. So, I feel kind of sorry for him. He looks like a vintage lampshade from a thrift shop.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: It's not that good.

utterances.utterance: He is trying to be Keith Richards every time he opens his mouth that obviously he's messed up. And it's kind of sad he thinks the President is messed up when he is talking he can barely focus.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Man in the mirror.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I mean, asked the secret service they are cool with celebrities making assassination jokes or beheading people or putting on assassination plays. The guys that are paid to protect the President, Republican or Democrat, they don't like these jokes. These jokes are funny. utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And just ruins it for the candidates on the left. I mean, this can't keep happening over and over and over again.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I think some of the people on the far left, especially the Hollywood types. utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Jane Fonda and Chelsea Handler and Alyssa Milano --

utterances.utterance: No, no, no. What you get is people coming in and drawing attention to Ossoff but not these far left positions that you guys delight in.

utterances.utterance: No, no, no. It's all over the mainstream media. And you see the celebrities going off, every day going cycle. Foaming at the mouth with the mainstream media. utterances.utterance: President Obama for his part blasted the Republican plan, posting a lengthy statement on Facebook that said in part, quote, "This bill will do you harm." utterances.utterance: That was a wine in. I think I'm going to be there tomorrow. Kimberly, there is a few conservative senators that have now come out and said, you know, what, I don't like this thing. And do you think that's going to be a problem?

utterances.utterance: Well, it's not great. Right? Because it's enough to create a problem for it not to get through. Obviously the President would like to see unanimous support. I mean, right? That would be a good idea.

utterances.utterance: And then say, listen, we understand. We hear your objections. And this is how we plan to address them going forward. Well, let's put this in and face it out. At least that was the argument that they were making before. There they are. These -- on the four.

utterances.utterance: Okay. Interesting concept. Juan, anything is better than ObamaCare?

utterances.utterance: But Juan, but Juan, the polls -- can I just say this?

utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The polls are measuring what people don't like it, what the media is saying about.

utterances.utterance: Because they're getting their information from you.

utterances.utterance: Is that how you guys past ObamaCare because --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The real opposition here, Susan Collins, Shelley Moore Capito --

utterances.utterance: Juan, we can refute all your things point by point but instead we will going to talk to Ainsley Earhardt who spoke to President Trump about health care. Roll the tape.

You know, health care is a very difficult situation. If you look, the Clintons tried to get it and after years and years, they couldn't do it. ObamaCare was murder for them to get. utterances.utterance: Okay. utterances.utterance: And it's going to be ugly.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Absolutely. Because at least, one thing about Nancy Pelosi and Reid before Chuck Schumer, they could actually keep their people rigorously --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: They ruled with an iron fist.

utterances.utterance: They did. They said, we are all voting together. We're voting a block. Republicans are much more for individualism. Right? They're like, everybody can have their own opinion and is just a little bit more messy but I think by the end of it, if they get it for the President to sign, it will be better legislation. utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: After seven years. Seven years. Repeal. We're going to repeal it. No repeal. It's what Greg said.

utterances.utterance: President Obama illegally transferred fronds from the Treasury Department in order to pay for ObamaCare. It was not even self-sustaining. That's why it's --

utterances.utterance: It's been self-sustaining. It's been sabotaged by Republicans.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: And if you don't like it so much, maybe you can reach across the aisle and maybe get --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I agree with that point.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know what ObamaCare is? It's like, one of the -- it's a huge awful tattoo that you got in your 20s. On your back. And it's like really hard to remove. And it is going to take a long time to remove it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: They are talking about Medicaid, Greg.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, I understand.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: They are actually saving and strengthening Medicaid, Juan.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Include tattoo removal on that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. And you guys can see Ainsley's full interview with President Trump tomorrow morning on "Fox & FRIENDS." President Trump says he doesn't want a poor person to run the economy. Is that a good idea? We will going to discuss it, up next.

utterances.utterance: There you go. But listen to this provocative comment from Mr. Trump while lauding the business accomplishments of his top economic advisors.

utterances.utterance: So somebody said, why did you appoint a rich person to be in charge of the economy?

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.utterance: I said -- no, it's true. And Wilbur is a very rich person in charge of commerce. I said because that's the kind of thinking we want. I mean, you know, really, because they are representing the country. They don't want the money. They love all people, rich or poor. But in those particular positions, I just don't want a poor person. utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.utterance: If you insist, I will do it. But I like it better this way, right?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: OK, how many people know what he meant by that, raise your hand?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: I'm seeing four hands so far. Juan Williams is confused.

utterances.utterance: I'm confused. I'm curious. What do you think he meant by that?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Wilbur Ross has been very successful. He is brilliant. He is in charge of commerce. You have Steven Mnuchin who is in charge of the treasury department. And so, when President Trump ran for office, he said I wanted to get the best and brightest out there available to help me...

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wait a second, wait a second.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Can I interrupt?

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: He didn't say that. He said the richest.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: No, no, no.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: He didn't say these are people who are experts.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: I said when he ran for office, this is what he promised.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, that's not what he said last night. He just said the richest.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: So he is saying it makes sense to have someone who...

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: If he said that, if he said what you said, I might buy into it.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Would you vote for me, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know I would. I can't help myself. I'm a big fan.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He basically said, I don't want a clumsy person to be my surgeon. I don't want to have a person with low upper body strength helping me move a couch.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: There are types of people, there is a class of person where you work hard, but you're in the industry where you will never get rich, that's not what he's saying. He is talking about the people that we know in our lives who are poor, no matter what they do with their money. No matter how much money they make, they are just not good with their finances. So we are saying somebody who is great with their finances, in charge of our finances. You want a great accountant who is good with money.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's amazing how pathetic the critics are. They know what he meant, but they don't care.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Johnny Depp is a very good actor, but he is very bad with finances. He really is.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: The rich are better than you and me. And the rich are going to be looking out for themselves, not looking out for the working man in America.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You should kill them, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan, you are rich.

utterances.speaker: GUILFOYLE
utterances.utterance: Juan, you are the richest man at this table.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan is wearing a white linen pants right now.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: White linen pants.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You guys, I'm standing up here, I'm giving testimonials.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You are the Wilbur Ross of The Five.

utterances.utterance: Oh, my God.

utterances.utterance: Listen, if Trump gives a speech for 90 minutes and this is the gap that the media is latching onto, I would take that any day.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, poor defense, Jesse.

utterances.utterance: So a couple weeks ago, Secretary of HUD -- Secretary of Housing and Urban Development Ben Carson.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS

utterances.utterance: He said poverty is a state of mind. And he was ridiculed for it. And then, you look at Jason Riley who wrote this really great op-ed.

utterances.utterance: Brilliant.

utterances.utterance: In the Wall Street Journal on Tuesday, in which listen to Ben Carson explain what he meant by that. He grew up poor. Now, he's trying to help poor people. I think that's what the president was saying. It reminded me of your book, Unspeakable Truths.

utterances.utterance: Thank you.

utterances.utterance: Well, it's a good book.

utterances.utterance: Yeah, exactly.

utterances.utterance: A hundred percent. That is why Ben Carson is in charge trying to elevate and lift people out of poverty, and get housing, and jobs. And that is what you want, right? utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Goldman Sachs for everything. Just let them take over.

utterances.utterance: All right. As everyone tries to figure out what to do with North Korea, National Review reveals a key fact: The world buys slaves from the place. utterances.utterance: Well, I think from that twit that he just twitted out, I think it was yesterday, where he said, you know what, China tried, too bad it didn't work.
